&gt; How to compare age which is Integer object for which I&#39;m unable to access age.intValue() also, Please let me know.

No, it&#39;s not. Because `age` is an `I`, it&#39;s an instance of that type variable (or null), which can be anything at all: an `Integer`, a `String`, an `Object`, a `List`, a `ClassThatIHaveJustWritten`...

If you need `age` to be an instance of `Integer`, declare it as one (or as an `int`, if you never expect it to be null), and you&#39;ll then have no trouble using `&lt;` to compare it - although you&#39;ll find it easier just to use the `Integer.compareTo` (or `Integer.compare`) instead.

----

If you _really_ need to compare things for a generic `I` (that is, not an `Integer`, contrary to what is stated in the question), you need to bound `I` so that it implements `Comparable` (as well as the `Students` class itself), which allows you to call the `compare` method on that:

```
class Students&lt;I extends Comparable&lt;? super I&gt;,S &gt; implements Comparable&lt;Students&lt;I,S&gt;&gt;{
    private I age;

    // ...
    public int compareTo(Students&lt;I, S&gt; s) {
      return age.compareTo(s.age);
    }
}
```

```
class Students&lt;I extends Comparable&lt;I&gt;, S&gt; implements Comparable&lt;Students&lt;I, S&gt;&gt; {
    private I age;
    private S name;

    public Students(I a, S n) {
        age = a;
        name = n;
    }

    public int compareTo(Students&lt;I, S&gt; s) {
        return age.compareTo(s.age);
    }

    public I getAge() {
        return age;
    }

    public S getName() {
        return name;
    }

    public String toString() {
        return &quot; &quot; + name;
    }
}
```

To resolve this, you can add a type constraint to I to ensure it extends the Comparable interface. This way, you can use the compareTo method on I to compare the age values.
The code I&#39;ve shared has the type parameter I is constrained to extend Comparable&lt;I&gt;, indicating that it should be a type that supports comparison. Inside the compareTo method, you can directly call the compareTo method on the age objects to compare them.
Hope this will work in your case.

As it currently is, you can&#39;t do it, since `I` and `S` now are `Object`s. You need to either:

 1. Introduce bounds for your generic parameters:
```
class Students&lt;I extends Comparable&lt;I&gt;, S extends Comparable&lt;S&gt;&gt; implements Comparable&lt;Students&lt;I, S&gt;&gt; {
  private final I age;
  private final S name;

  public Students(I age, S name) {
    this.age = age;
    this.name = name;
  }

  @Override
  public int compareTo(Students&lt;I, S&gt; s) {
    int cmp = this.age.compareTo(s.age);
    if (cmp != 0) {
      return cmp;
    }
    return this.name.compareTo(s.name);
  }
}
```
Like this `I` and `S` can be only types that implement `Comparable` and you can use their `compareTo()` methods.

 2. Or you can depend on [Comparators][1] to make the comparison for you.
```
class Students&lt;I, S&gt; implements Comparable&lt;Students&lt;I, S&gt;&gt; {

  private final I age;
  private final S name;
  private final Comparator&lt;I&gt; ageComparator;
  private final Comparator&lt;S&gt; nameComparator;

  public Students(I age, S name, Comparator&lt;I&gt; ageComparator, Comparator&lt;S&gt; nameComparator) {
    this.age = age;
    this.name = name;
    this.ageComparator = ageComparator;
    this.nameComparator = nameComparator;
  }

  @Override
  public int compareTo(Students&lt;I, S&gt; s) {
    int cmp = ageComparator.compare(this.age, s.age);
    if (cmp != 0) {
      return cmp;
    }
    return nameComparator.compare(this.name, s.name);
  }
}
```
**Warning**: The second option is not really recommended, as it may break a general requirement of `Comparable` - `The implementor must ensure signum(x.compareTo(y)) == -signum(y.compareTo(x)) for all x and y.` I would only use it as a last resort.

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Comparator.html

